===============================================================================
SECURED AND MONITORED WEB INFRASTRUCTURE - EXPLANATION
===============================================================================

What happens when a user requests "https://www.foobar.com"?

To view the diagram of the secured and monitored web infrastructure, click here:
https://imgur.com/IorIfzp

## STEP 1: HTTPS REQUEST AND DNS RESOLUTION

The user types "https://www.foobar.com" in the browser. The DNS translates
the domain name into the public IP address of the Load Balancer.

- WHY HTTPS? Traffic is served over HTTPS using an SSL CERTIFICATE to encrypt
  data traveling between the user and the infrastructure. This prevents
  hackers from intercepting sensitive information like passwords.

## STEP 2: FIREWALL 1 AND THE LOAD BALANCER

Before reaching the Load Balancer, the request passes through FIREWALL 1.

- WHAT ARE FIREWALLS FOR? Firewalls act as security guards. They filter
  incoming and outgoing network traffic based on strict rules to block
  unauthorized access and cyberattacks.
- FIREWALL 1 RULES: This is a public firewall. It only allows traffic on
  PORT 80 (HTTP) and PORT 443 (HTTPS). All other ports are closed.

The Load Balancer (HAProxy) receives the secure request and performs SSL
TERMINATION. It decrypts the HTTPS traffic using the SSL certificate, then
forwards the request as plain text to the backend servers.

## STEP 3: FIREWALLS 2 & 3 AND THE BACKEND SERVERS (Server 1 & Server 2)

The decrypted request travels to Server 1 or Server 2. To enter, it must pass
through FIREWALL 2 or FIREWALL 3.

- FIREWALL 2 & 3 RULES: These are private firewalls. They ONLY accept traffic
  coming from the Load Balancer's IP address. Anyone trying to attack the
  servers directly without passing through the Load Balancer will be blocked.

Inside the server, the regular LAMP/Nginx process takes place (Nginx ->
Application Server -> Codebase).

## STEP 4: MONITORING CLIENTS (Data Collectors)

A monitoring client (data collector agent like Sumo Logic or Datadog) is
installed on the Load Balancer, Server 1, and Server 2.

- WHAT IS MONITORING USED FOR? It monitors system health, tracks performance,
  and alerts sysadmins immediately if a component fails or overloads.
- HOW IT COLLECTS DATA: The monitoring agent runs in the background. It
  constantly reads system logs and queries system metrics (CPU, RAM, disk
  usage). It then pushes this data over the internet to a central monitoring
  service dashboard.
- MONITORING WEB SERVER QPS: To monitor Nginx QPS (Queries Per Second), the
  agent parses the Nginx access logs ("access.log") or hooks into the Nginx
  status module ("http_stub_status_module") to count and graph the number of
  incoming requests every second.

===============================================================================
ISSUES WITH THIS INFRASTRUCTURE
===============================================================================

1. SSL TERMINATION AT THE LOAD BALANCER LEVEL:
   Because SSL decryption happens at the Load Balancer, the traffic between the
   Load Balancer and the backend servers travels in CLEAR TEXT over the private
   network. If an attacker breaches the internal network, they can sniff the data.

2. ONLY ONE MYSQL SERVER ACCEPTING WRITES:
   The Primary Database node is still a SPOF for write operations. If it crashes,
   the website becomes read-only (users cannot sign up, update profiles, or post).
   The architecture cannot automatically promote the Replica to Primary.

3. SERVERS WITH ALL THE SAME COMPONENTS:
   Running Nginx, the Application Server, and MySQL together on the same machine
   causes resource competition. MySQL could consume all the RAM and crash Nginx.
   It also makes scaling inefficient, as you cannot scale the database and the
   web server independently.
